{"type":"message","id":"cbe5a9ac","parentId":"30cdb65c","timestamp":"2026-03-02T05:47:57.145Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Done. Policy is structured and concise with all the requested elements.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Done. `system/policy.md` populated:\n\n**Loops:** Heartbeat (~30s) sends due messages; Orchestrator (~15m) picks one domain, one action\n\n**Quiet hours:** 00:00–05:00 IST — no outbound, no user-artifact writes\n\n**Phases:** 1 = experiment/learn → 2 = daily briefs\n\n**Daily briefs:** 05:00 IST, one per domain, ultra-concise\n\n**Urgency:** Explicit `urgent` OR due same day → only these get persistent reminders\n\n**User-artifacts:** Read anytime, write only outside quiet hours\n\nReady for next."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"zai","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":391,"output":152,"cacheRead":16960,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":17503,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772430468896}}
{"type":"message","id":"76b349ce","parentId":"cbe5a9ac","timestamp":"2026-03-02T05:48:06.378Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Mon 2026-03-02 05:48 UTC] Define Queue Schema Document the schema inside /system/queue.jsonl as comments at the top (or in a separate schema section if needed). Each entry must contain: channel_id due_at_utc due_at_user user_tz messages (array of 1+ strings) Add instruction: Due logic uses UTC only. Messages are sent in order. Heartbeat is dumb; it only checks due_at_utc."}],"timestamp":1772430486376}}
{"type":"message","id":"8045478b","parentId":"76b349ce","timestamp":"2026-03-02T05:48:28.123Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to document a queue schema. Since queue.jsonl is a JSONL file (JSON Lines), I can't put comments at the top in standard JSON. However, I could:\n\n1. Put the schema documentation as a separate file\n2. Use a JSONL \"comment\" convention where the first line is a special metadata line\n3. Just document it inline\n\nGiven that JSONL files are typically data files, I think the cleanest approach is to either:\n- Create a separate schema file (queue.schema.md)\n- Or put a special schema-comment line at the top of the JSONL\n\nLet me just add a documentation block at the top of the file. JSONL doesn't officially support comments, but I can make the first line a schema reference or create a separate schema file.\n\nActually, the user said \"as comments at the top (or in a separate schema section if needed)\". Since JSONL doesn't support comments, I'll create a separate schema documentation file, or I can embed the schema as the first \"record\" in the JSONL that serves as documentation.\n\nLet me create a queue.schema.md file instead, since that's cleaner for documentation purposes. Or I can just write the schema documentation directly into queue.jsonl as a pseudo-comment block (some systems use { \"_comment\": \"...\" } as the first line).\n\nI'll go with a clean approach: write the schema documentation into the file as a JSON \"comment\" object at the top, which is a common pattern.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1d3bf1714d1343d5a77060c9","name":"write","arguments":{"file_path":"/root/.openclaw/workspace/system/queue.jsonl","content":"{\"_schema\": true, \"note\": \"Queue schema documentation. Delete this line in production.\", \"fields\": {\"channel_id\": \"Target channel for delivery\", \"due_at_utc\": \"ISO 8601 UTC timestamp for due logic\", \"d